<div class="section">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="grid-12">
      <h2>Auto grid sizes</h2>
      <p>Or you can just add an element with the class <code>grid</code> and let the grid figure it out. And if you need a column to be a set size you just add grid size you need as in the example before.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row demo">
    <div class="grid"><span>Auto</span></div>
    <div class="grid"><span>Auto</span></div>
    <div class="grid"><span>Auto</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="row demo">
    <div class="grid"><span>Auto</span></div>
    <div class="grid-8"><span>8</span></div>
    <div class="grid"><span>Auto</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="grid-12">
      <pre><code>&lt;div class="row"&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid"&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid"&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid"&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="row"&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid"&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid-8"&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid"&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="grid-12">
      <h2>Fluid grids</h2>
      <p>By default, a row is always 1200 pixels wide on screen. But to make a row fluid you just need to change your class from <code>row</code> to <code>row--width-fluid</code>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row--width-fluid demo">
    <div class="grid-4"><span>4</span></div>
    <div class="grid-4"><span>4</span></div>
    <div class="grid-4"><span>4</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="row--width-fluid demo">
    <div class="grid-3"><span>3</span></div>
    <div class="grid-6"><span>6</span></div>
    <div class="grid-3"><span>3</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="row--width-fluid demo">
    <div class="grid-2"><span>2</span></div>
    <div class="grid-8"><span>8</span></div>
    <div class="grid-2"><span>2</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="grid-12">
      <pre><code>&lt;div class="row--width-fluid"&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid-4"&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid-6"&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="grid-12">
      <h2>Grid offsetting</h2>
      <p>Amazium also has the option to offset a column, which should make life all the bit easier if you you need to add an extra bit of space between columns. This is done by adding a modifier class of as many columns you want the offset i.e. if you want to have an offset of 4 then a column of 8 all you need to do is add <code>grid--offset-4</code> after grid-8.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row demo">
    <div class="grid-8"><span>8</span></div>
    <div class="grid-2 grid--offset-2"><span>2</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="row demo">
    <div class="grid-4"><span>4</span></div>
    <div class="grid-4 grid--offset-4"><span>4</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="row demo">
    <div class="grid-7 grid--offset-5"><span>7</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="grid-12">
      <pre><code>&lt;div class="row"&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid-6"&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid-3 grid--offset-3"&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="grid-12">
      <h2>Nesting grids</h2>
      <p>If you wanted to nest two columns inside a larger this is no problem either as the below code shows and there is no need to add / change your CSS either..!.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row demo">
    <div class="grid-12">
      <span>
        <p>12</p>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="grid-5"><span>Nested 5</span></div>
          <div class="grid-7"><span>Nested 7</span></div>
        </div>
      </span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="grid-12">
      <pre><code>&lt;div class="row"&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid-12"&gt;
    ...
